    <DocumentationNarrative Id="source:cli:meta-sql:app:narrative:guide:working-with-metasql" DocumentationSubjectId="source:cli:meta-sql:app" PreviousNarrativeId="source:cli:meta-sql:app:narrative:summary:summary">
      <Body>MetaSql represents a database and its deployable SQL structure as a modeled workspace. Tables, views, procedures, functions, dependencies, and deployment evidence are available as data that can be inspected, compared, generated, and consumed by other models.

Authoring and deployment have distinct responsibilities. A deploy manifest records the source and live fingerprints that must agree before SQL is applied, turning release readiness into an explicit modeled decision. Generated SQL therefore has a traceable source workspace and a clear contract for the database it is about to change.

MetaSql is the physical SQL boundary for sanctioned converters and generated assets. It provides a natural database-facing representation while staying connected to the source schema, transform, vault, warehouse, or data-quality model that gave the SQL its meaning.</Body>
      <BodyFormat>Markdown</BodyFormat>
      <Origin>Authored</Origin>
      <ReviewStatus>Current</ReviewStatus>
      <Slot>Guide</Slot>
      <Title>Working with MetaSql</Title>
